metadata.value:
Tours of Historic Houses Charleston, South Carolina Histories of the Houses Compiled by Samuel Gaillard Stoney Charleston is a living history book, with streets and doorways, walls and gardens speaking eloquently of famous men of the past and their culture. Its lovely houses, still used and valued as the finest homes in the city today, are the tangible, vivid signs of a heritage that belongs to the whole country. Each year thousands of visitors come to see Charlestons world-famous gardens, to walk its streets and look at its historic buildings. Here Georgian, Baroque, Adam, Classic Colonial and Greek Revival rub shoulders with two Charleston innovations, the long piazza designed for the climate and the "single" house, gable end to the street and one room wide. Now for the first time visitors are invited through the piazza door and the garden gate. In the five week period from March 15 through April 16, 1948, during the spring flowering that is cultural as well as horticultural, twenty-three of these famous houses will be open to the public in nine tours sponsored by Historic Charleston Foundation. Historic Charleston Foundation, a non-profit, educational institution, seeks to preserve and use the architectural and historic treasures of the Charleston area, not as museums but as living parts of the community. With funds from gifts [which are tax free], bequests, and the operation of tours, the Foundation offers planning and financial aid to preserve Charlestons heritage not only for those who live here but for all who come to enjoy its beauty. General Information TOURS: Four tours will be offered each day, Monday through Friday, with a special tour each Friday evening. The first four tours, lettered A through D, will be shown March 15 through 31. The second four tours, E through H, will be shown April 1 through 16. The fee for each daytime tour is $2.00 plus tax. The special evening tour is $1.00 plus tax. Transportation, if desired, will be available at reasonable cost. Full information and tour tickets may be secured from the tour headquarters in the Dock Street Theatre. RESERVATIONS: It is advisable to make room reservations before coming to Charleston. Write to the hotels listed below, or to the Charleston Chamber of Commerce which lists rooms available in private homes. Hotels and Inns Argyle Hotel'Single, $2 up; Double, $2.50 up. Brewton Inn'Single, $5; Double, $6 up. Charleston Hotel'Single, $2 up; Double, $4 up. Fort Sumter Hotel'Single, $4 up; Double $8 up. Francis Marion Hotel'Single, $2 up; Double, $3 up. St. John Hotel'Single, $3 up; Double, $4.50 up. Timrod Hotel'Single, $2 up; Double, $2.50 up. Villa Margharita'Write for rates. TRAVEL INFORMATION: Charleston is served by the Atlantic Coast Line Railroad and the Southern Railway; by the Delta Airlines, Eastern Airlines and National Airlines; by the Greyhound Bus Line; and by U. S. Highways 17, 52, and 78. Tours presented only on the dates and hours listed. TOUR A 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., March 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 29, 30, 31. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., March 22, 23, 24, 25, 26. DOCK STREET THEATRE. 135 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. The first theatre in America was Charlestons Dock Street Theatre. The present building, a reconstruction of the eighteenth century playhouse, incorporates the balcony and famous facade of the Planters Hotel. The Adam style interior woodwork is from the home of Judge Mitchell King where such eminent visitors as Thackeray and MacCready, the actor, were entertained. Operated by the Carolina Art Association as a community theatre and school of the drama. EDMONSTON-ALSTON HOUSE. 21 East Battery, c. 1828. Built by Charles Edmonston, prosperous merchant, on the foundations of the Revolutionary Fort Mechanic, this Greek Revival residence overlooking the harbor was later bought by the noted Alston family. Now the home of J. J. Pringle Smith, owner of famous Middleton Place, oldest landscape gardens in America. HEYWARD-WASHINGTON HOUSE. 87 Church Street, c. 1770. George Washington was lodged for a week at this home of Thomas Heyward, signer of the Declaration of Independence, during his Southern tour in 1791. The furnishings and formal garden are in the period of the first President. Owned by the Charleston Museum. HUMPHREY SOMMERS TENEMENT. 2 Be- dons Alley. 1778. Humphrey Sommers, who made a fortune building St. Michaels church and a number of houses here, built this as a store with a residence above. In 1928 Mr. and Mrs. James Conner adapted its excellent proportions for use as their residence. TOUR B 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., March 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 29, 30, 31. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m, March 22, 23, 24, 25, 26. DOCK STREET THEATRE: 13 5 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. [See Tour A]. WILLIAM GIBBES HOUSE. 64 South Battery, 1772. William Gibbes, wealthy shipowner, built this splendid Georgian mansion overlooking the wharf where his business was conducted. Later owners who enriched the woodwork with tasteful Adam ornaments included Rev. John Grimke Drayton, who owned Magnolia Gardens, and Mrs. Washington A. Roebling, widow of the builder of the Brooklyn Bridge. Now the home of Mr. and Mrs. John Ashby Farrow. DRAYTON-MANIGAULT HOUSE. 6 Gibbes Street. 1806. Built when Gibbes Street was still at the waterside, this house has been owned and occupied by many notable families. A very fine example of building for Comfort and entertainment, with due attention to appearance, this dweUing is now the home of Mr. and Mrs. Francis G. Boggs. SIMMONS-EDWARDS HOUSE. 14 Leg are Street, c. 1800. Francis Simmons, who built this house, created a Charleston mystery by leaving his wife immediately after the marriage. A later owner, George Edwards, added the fine iron grills and fence with finials, made to order in Italy. Now the home of Mrs. Louise Foster-Brown. TOUR C 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., March 22, 23, 24, 25, 26. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., March 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 29, 30, 31. DOCK STREET THEATRE. 135 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. [See Tour A.] YOUNG-JOHNSON HOUSE. 35 Church Street, c. 1770. Thomas Young built this characteristic "single" dwelling which later housed Dr. Joseph Johnson, Intendant of Charleston, president of the branch Bank of the United States. The present owner, Mr. Wilmer Hoffman, has restored and redecorated the house, using some of his own famous sculpture as well as notable furniture, paintings and objects of art. JAMES HUSTONS HOUSE. 131 Church Street, c. 1809. James Huston, merchant- tailor, built this house with shop below and living quarters above on land that once belonged to Joseph Blake, Landgrave, Proprietor, and Governor of Carolina. Now the home of Dr. and Mrs. I. Grier Linton. OTHNIEL BEALES HOUSE. 101 East Bay Street. 1741. Captain Beale, an Engineer officer who reconstructed the fortifications of Charleston, built this house and the one to the south of it, with fine cypress-panelled rooms above and merchants stores below, Now the residence of Mr. and Mrs. Lionel K. Legge, who pioneered here in 1931 in the rehabilitation of this block, known as "Rainbow Row." TOUR D 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., March 22, 23, 24, 25, 26. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., March 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 29, 30, 31. DOCK STREET THEATRE. 135 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. [See Tour A.] JOSEPH WINTHROPS HOUSE. 129 Tradd Street. 1797. Mary Fraser, sister of the famous miniaturist and writer, Charles Fraser, brought the land for this house to her husband, Joseph Winthrop, a Massachusetts merchant who settled in Charleston. The two parlors exist almost as built, with fine gouge woodwork in place of Adam putty ornament; the dining room mantel was taken from the home of Henry Laurens, president of the Continental Congress. Now the home of Commodore and Mrs. W. S. Popham. CAPTAIN JOHN MORRISONS HOUSE. 125 Tradd Street. 1807. John Morrison, successful mariner and merchant, built this large fine "single" house in the typical Charleston manner. The present owner, Mr. Frederic Stevens Allen, uses it as a winter home, having added greatly to its charm by renovation and skillful furnishings.  JOSEPH MANIGAULTS HOUSE. 350 Meeting Street. 1803. Gabriel Manigault, Charlestons famous amateur architect, built this house for his brother, Joseph. An outstanding example of domestic architecture of the Adam period, the house contains a lovely ballroom and stairway. A secret staircase leads from the second floor to the third. A gate-keepers lodge adds charm to the garden entrance. Owned by the Charleston Museum. TOUR E 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., April 1, 2, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., April 12, 13, 14, 15, 16. DOCK STREET THEATRE. 135 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. [See Tour A.] WILLIAM HENDRICKS TENEMENTS. 83 Church Street. 1749. Shortly after the fire of 1740 cleared this part of town William Hendricks, planter, of Christ Church parish, started building these agreeable little twin houses for investment. They were used for businesses of various sorts for nearly two centuries. In 1936 the rear house was converted into a very interesting residence by its present owners, Mr. and Mrs. Reynolds D. Brown. HEYWARD-WASHINGTON HOUSE. 87 Church Street, c. 1770. [See Tour A]. THOMAS LEGARES HOUSE. 90 Church Street, c. 1760. Built by an early Huguenot merchant, this is a very handsome "single" house of the fine mid-Georgian period. Long the residence and place of business of Charleston merchants, it is now the home of Mr. W. Lucas Simons. TOUR F 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., April 1, 2, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., April 12, 13, 14, 15, 16. DOCK STREET THEATRE. 135 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. [See Tour A.] THOMAS ROSES HOUSE. 59 Church Street. 1735. This house, apparently built by Thomas and Beuler Rose in a section then called Baptist Town, later figured in a tragic and romantic duel. Dr. Joseph Ladd Brown, living there in 1786, got into a row about the local performance of a lovely actress. Fatally wounded in a duel that followed, Brown, only twenty-two, died in the house. Handsomely restored by the Frank E. Whitmans, in 1929, it is now the residence of Mr. and Mrs. Henry P. Staats. ADAM TUNNOS HOUSE. 89 East Bay Street, c. 1780. Built by John Deas, this house was for forty-three years the home and place of business of Adam Tunno, president of the St. Andrews Society and acknowledged "king" of the Scotch merchants in Charleston. Now the home of Mrs. Alexander Martin. GEORGE EVELEIGHS HOUSE. 39 Church Street, c. 1738. This house was built by George Eveleigh, one of the heads of Charlestons great Indian trade, who enriched himself by bartering British goods for deer skins all over the Southeast. Later occupied by Dr. John Louis Polony, famous botanist and emigre from the French Revolution, it has long been the property of the Marshall family and is now the residence of Miss Mary O. Marshall. TOUR G 10 a.m. to 1 p.m., April 12, 13, 14, 15, 16. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m., April 1, 2, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9. DOCK STREET THEATRE. 135 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. [See Tour A.] CAPERS-HUGER-SMITH HOUSE. 69 Church Street, c. 1745. This fine example of a "double" house was built by Richard Capers, Later it became the residence of Colonel Jacob Motte, treasurer of the Province and ancestor of many notable Revolutionary figures. Purchased by Mrs. William Mason Smith in 1869, it has continued in her family and is now the home of her grand-daughters, Miss Caroline R. Huger Smith and Miss Alice R. Huger Smith, noted water-colorist. COLONEL ISAAC MOTTES HOUSE. 30 Meeting Street. 1769. Tradition says that Thomas Young, a builder, began this house and then sold it unfinished to Isaac Motte, who fought in the American Revolution. It descended in his family for nearly two hundred years. It is now the residence of Mrs. Victor Morawetz. COLONEL WILLIAM RHETTS HOUSE. 54 Hasell Street. 1712, This house was built on a suburban plantation by William Rhett, vice-admiral of the Province of Carolina, who won fame by capturing Stede Bonnet and clearing this coast of pirates in 1718. It later served as the birthplace of the famous governor of South Carolina, Wade Hampton. Now one of the oldest dwelling houses in Charleston, it has been restored and used as a residence by Mr. and Mrs. Benjamin Kitt- redge, Jr., whose parents own the famous Cypress Gardens. [Note: This house will not be shown April 1 and 2]. TOUR H 10 a.m. to 1 p.m, April 12, 13, 14, 15, 16. 3 p.m. to 6 p.m, April 1, 2, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9. DOCK STREET THEATRE. 135 Church Street. 1736'Reconstructed. [See Tour A.] ASHLEY HALL. 172 Rutledge Avenue, c. 1816. Patrick Duncan, who made a pleasant fortune as a tallow-chandler and factor, built this massive Regency house. It was later occupied by James Reid Pringle and still later by George A. Trenholm, a great Charleston merchant and Secretary of the Treasury of the Confederate States. Especially notable are the mantels and the fine stairway spiralling up to a Ceiling light of colored glass. Since 1909 it has been a famous southern school for girls, under the direction of Dr. Mary Vardrine McBee. JOSEPH MANIGAULTS HOUSE. 350 Meeting Street. 1803. [See Tour D.] ROBERT HUME LUCAS HOUSE. 178 Ashley Avenue. 1850. This handsome Greek Revival house was built in a fashionable suburb, then known as Cannonsboro, by Robert Hume Lucas, a member of a great family of rice planters and millers. Now the residence of Mr. and Mrs. A. O. Neese. SPECIAL EVENING TOUR 8 p.m. to 10 p.m, March 19, 26; April 2, 9, 16. TIMOTHY FORDS HOUSE. 54 Meeting Street. 1800. This very handsome house in the Adam style was built by Timothy Ford, a native of New Jersey who became a Charles- tonian. It was owned by his descendants, the Ravenels, for over a century. According to tradition, Lafayette was entertained here. Now the residence of Dr. and Mrs. Ransom S. Hooker. Note: Samuel Gaillard Stoney, a member of the Board of Trustees of Historic Charleston Foundation, is vice- president of the Historical Society of South Carolina, vice-president of the Huguenot Society, Honorary Curator of South Carolina Culture at the Charleston Museum, Honorary Curator of the Charleston Free Library of the County of Charleston, and member of the executive board of the Carolina Art Association.
